Anonymous Mon 05 Apr 2021 21:47:07 No.37679766 Report
Quoted By: >>37679814 >>37679952 >>37680247 >>37680849 >>37683664
Feedback guy from the other thread here, I've finally got through (most) of the list and written up some stuff. Gonna have to split this up across three or four posts.

Okay, first up: Secrets of the Don.

This was a genuinely excellent read. The premise is interesting and, so far, has been executed damn near flawlessly. The protagonist is written incredibly well and the reader really gets inside their head, which should obviously be a given what with being in first person, but a lot of what I will call “amateur” writing often doesn’t do a good job of that even in first person works and it’s really nice to see. It’s also nice to see that Dom has some genuine flaws (which I suppose he would do, being a mobster and all) balanced with his wit and altruistic streak. I was completely drawn into Dom’s life and the struggles he finds himself caught up in between Marcia and his criminal past slowly crawling out of the woodwork.

Speaking of Marcia, she’s adorable but most importantly also feels like an actual person with her own thoughts and feelings. Her relationship with Dom develops incredibly naturally, and the explosive conflict between the two of them when Dom’s cover-up gets blown felt just as real. I’m really looking forwards to seeing how they work things out from here, as well as seeing how they deal with things inevitably getting a whole lost worse between Dom and the mob in the future.

One thing I do find myself wishing got a bit more page time was Dom’s relationship with Angelo, though. Visiting the Don in prison is made out to be a hugely significant thing for Dom, but past the initial meeting he kind of drops out of the story despite Dom presumably keeping to his monthly meeting schedule. Ironically as the mob looms larger and larger over Dom’s life, the Don’s presence diminishes which does feel a little bit odd to me.

(Cont.)
